      "writtenOn": "2026-04-13T23:09:39Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "What is the goal of this flag throughout this commit?\n* To allow for early testing of JSON config files on very early hardware/simulation before all the GPIOs have been set up in the kernel?\n* To allow for automated testing?\n\nThe solution for the two is very different I think.\n\n## Suggestions if trying to allow for early testing\n\nHardcoding this in the C++ class seems like it won\u0027t work for upstream code. One user of the application might want to have it false, and another might want it to be true.\n\nYou could make it a command line parameter or a build flag.\n\nHowever, a simpler approach might be to do the following:\n* Don\u0027t create the gpiod::line object in the constructor. This allows the constructor to succeed and the Gpio object to exist.\n* Create the gpiod::line object if needed when one of the Gpio request methods is called. Throw an exception then if the find_line() fails.\n* Let the caller of the Gpio request method decide how to handle the exception. They could choose to retry a few times and then log an error message.\n\nThis would eliminate the need for all the JSON parser changes.\n\n## Suggestions if trying to allow for automated testing\n\nIn this case, I\u0027d suggest using the standard approach of:\n* Abstract base GPIO class\n* Concrete sub-class that does the real thing\n* Mock sub-class for automated tests\n\nYou already have the first two, and creating the mock class is very simple. Then you just have to decide how to cause the real subclass to be created for production usage and the mock subclass to be created for automated tests.\n\nTwo approaches used in this repository:\n* Create a Services hierarchy with the same three classes (ABC/real/mock). Add a createGPIO method to the Services class. The real subclass creates a real GPIO, and the mock subclass creates a mock GPIO. This Services hierarchy can handle other real/mock problems in the future too, such as error logging and getting data from D-Bus.\n* Create a global scope createGPIO function in the GPIO header file. Provide two implementations in two different .C files. Then link in the implementation that produces a real GPIO when linking the real application. Link in the implementation that produces a mock GPIO when linking the test cases.",
      "revId": "54dec7bad6574472c69dbc225e1ae81a383cda20",
      "serverId": "adbd0a64-1f21-4d83-b585-671fe73cb6e4"
